data.content:
## What breaks

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous LINQ by opting into **sync-over-async** (blocking on async calls internally). In **.NET 11, that bridge is removed entirely**. Every synchronous call on the Cosmos provider — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

## The fix

Convert every sync call to its async counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods become `async` and use `await`
- `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`

This will ripple up through your call stack — callers of these methods will also need to go async (`async`/`await` all the way up to the controller actions).
